						               													<description>Foil is a board game primarily for two opponents. However, the board design allows configurations for more players.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each player has a source node from which his/her pieces originate. The object of the game is to remove the opponent's piece on his/her source node.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each piece is a six-sided dice, where each face represents a state. A turn consists of a player using a piece to &amp;quot;act&amp;quot; and then be removed from the board. Depending on the state, the piece can act on:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;a) An empty node&amp;#10;b) One of his/her own pieces&amp;#10;c) One of the opponent's pieces&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The remaining player's pieces then sequentially back-fill the empty node until the source node is left uncovered. The player can then add a piece of any state to the source node.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;There is one exception: the Thrust! In a &amp;quot;Thrust&amp;quot;, a player moves a piece from one node to another. The backfill process on proceeds to the baseline, whereby an empty node is left. In an &amp;quot;Thrust&amp;quot; move, the source node is left unchanged.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The &amp;quot;states&amp;quot; of the pieces are as follows:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;1) Neutral&amp;#10;2) Create  - adds a peice of Neutral State to the board&amp;#10;3) Change  - changes the state of any of the players pieces to another state&amp;#10;4) Recruit - changes opponent's pieces of State 4 or less to players own piece of Neutral State&amp;#10;5) Eject   - removes opponents piece of State 5 or less&amp;#10;6) Block   - acts as barrier to other states. Can sacrifice itself to remove other adjoacent opponent's piece of State 6&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
